		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2018 SI"></a><br><code>sle2018s/paper03</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2018 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Purely functional GLL parsing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LThomasvanBinsbergen.html">L. Thomas van Binsbergen</a>, <a href="../profile/ElizabethScott.html">Elizabeth Scott</a>, <a href="../profile/AdrianJohnstone.html">Adrian Johnstone</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cola.2020.100945">10.1016/j.cola.2020.100945</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2018/paper16.html"><em>GLL parsing with flexible combinators</em></a> (SLE 2018)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The paper develops a generalised parsing procedure (FUN-GLL) and derives parser combinators, i.e., core front-end technology in the compilation pipeline.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It provides an embedded “BNF combinator library” that effectively acts as a meta-language for writing executable syntax specifications with semantic actions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> It includes quantitative comparisons of alternative implementations, focusing on practical parsing overheads and efficiency trade-offs.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
